See also:  &quot;Liberty Bells Tour Washington:  Northwest Girls at Capital Sure 1776 Herald Will Come to 1915 Fair,&quot; <i>San Francisco Call</i>, 21 June 1913, p. 5.  An excerpt:

&quot;Philip S. Bates, publisher of the Pacific Northwest, who is responsible for the tour, gives assurances that the young women, most of whom are school teachers, while endowed with more than their usual share of comeliness, were chosen for what they know rather than for how they looked, as all first were required to pass a competitive examination given before the Portland, Ore., Chamber of Commerce.  The principal test was to tell how the applicant thought her particular locality in the west would be the most advantageous for the prospective settler to locate in....

&quot;The fiber of the young women may be judged from the fact that Miss Dawson, who is a school teacher in Harney county, Oregon, which she proudly calls 'the great interior empire of Oregon,' in order to reach Portland was compelled to travel nearly 200 miles over mountain ranges on horseback and stage coach before reaching the railroad.&quot;
